---
description: Godot GDScript coding standards for gameplay code.
globs: ["**/*.gd"]
alwaysApply: false
---

GDScript rules (see [docs/engineering/game-logic.md](docs/engineering/game-logic.md) for ownership):

- Use clear, small nodes/scripts with single responsibility.
- Prefer composition over deep inheritance; use `@tool` only when editor tooling needs it.
- Use `class_name` for shared types referenced across scenes and resources.
- Prefer typed GDScript: typed variables, parameters, and return types where practical.
- Use custom Resource classes for static design data; avoid hardcoded gameplay values in scripts when the value belongs in data.
- Do not use `get_node()`, `$NodePath`, or string-based lookups in runtime hot paths (`_process`, `_physics_process`, combat loops).
- Cache node and component references in `_ready()` or an explicit `initialize()` called once at setup.
- Use signals, autoloads, or small service nodes for decoupled systems — avoid spaghetti callbacks.
- Avoid static mutable global state except for carefully controlled autoload bootstrap services.
- Avoid allocations in `_process`, `_physics_process`, and frequently called combat methods.
- Use object pooling for enemies, projectiles, floating text, and VFX.
- Keep `_process` / `_physics_process` minimal; prefer timers and signal-driven updates when possible.
- Prefer `@export` and `@export_group` over public mutable fields without intent.
- Use `@export var` with typed resources (`TowerData`, `EnemyData`, etc.) instead of loose dictionaries for design data.
- Validate exported references in `_ready()` or editor `@tool` checks where useful.
